[http://www.flickr.com/photos/pellethepoet] Hmmm - possibly another <i>mea culpa</i>.  2 + 2 = 5 in my world!  

I was going on the similar contents (but not the same) album  <a href="http://acms.sl.nsw.gov.au/album/ItemViewer.aspx?itemid=823409&amp;suppress=N&amp;imgindex=2" rel="nofollow">title page</a> in the <a href="http://acms.sl.nsw.gov.au/item/itemDetailPaged.aspx?itemID=442753" rel="nofollow">SLNSW album</a>, which says &quot;At the request of the Secretary of State for the Colonies [ie in London] ... negatives taken by Charles Pickering under the direction of James Barnet ... [printed] 1872 &quot;.  

Also in the SLNSW blurb is this - &quot;On most album pages, at the lower right of image, appears a handwritten &quot;SH&quot; and a number in pencil. This referes to the Government Printing Office file number, with &quot;SH&quot; denoting John Sharkey, who possessed a large number of Charles Pickering's negatives. -- Reference: Alan Clifford, Government Printing Office, 1985. &quot;
